As shown above, physical eigenstates of j = (\Sigma ) are eigenstates of ^A \Sigma ^G. Eq. (2.19) implies that ^A and ^G commute. Suppose that the vector ~a represents a physical state in the j = (+) basis, as in Eq. (2.16). Since ^A and ^G commute, ~a is a simultaneous eigenvector of

^A and ^G, say with eigenvalues _2 and \Delta , respectively. Similarly, suppose that the vector

~b represents a physical state in the j = (\Gamma ) basis; ~b is also a simultaneous eigenvector of ^A

and ^G. There are then two possibilities: ~a and ~b have different eigenvalues in which case ~a \Delta ~b = 0, or ~a and ~b have the same eigenvalues in which case j~a \Delta ~bj = 1. Therefore, if we

assume that there are no degenerate states of the same normality, it follows that only pairs of states with masses _2 \Sigma \Delta communicate by single-pion emission and absorption. Since ~a and ~b are the physical states defined in Eq. (2.16), it follows immediately that jgfiffssj = 1

if ff and fi are paired, or gfiffss = 0, otherwise. This result is completely general and applies to all * = 0 states of the I = 12 mesons4. These mesons come in two varieties: Kaons

4 In what follows, when we refer to the algebraic content of chiral symmetry, or the consequences of unbroken chiral symmetry, we will have this general consequence of the three chiral commutation relations in mind.

11 and heavy mesons (D- and B-mesons). The Kaons are best suited to phenomenological analysis, and will be investigated later. However, the interactions of heavy mesons with pions are also constrained by heavy quark symmetry.

3. Heavy Quark Symmetry

In general, it is problematic to study pion-meson interactions in a systematic lagrangian formulation. For example, the ae meson can decay to two pions inside any Feynman diagram in which it appears. This decay generates a momentum transfer of order the ae mass, and is therefore not consistent with chiral power counting. So in studying the representations of unbroken chiral symmetry involving ae, one loses touch with the systematic effective lagrangian language5. In order to specialize to the subset of all chiral tree graphs -- which was essential in deriving the algebraic sum rules-- one must fall back on the large-N

c approximation [5,7]. When heavy mesons are involved, the situation is somewhat ameliorated since heavy quark symmetry implies helpful degeneracies. In particular, we

can justify the chiral tree approximation without invoking the large-Nc approximation if we are willing to assume that the mass splitting between any two members of a given heavy meson chiral multiplet is small compared to \Lambda O/. As long as this is the case, restriction to chiral tree graphs is automatic when one works to leading order in O/P T . Of course in O/P T there are tree graphs with any number of derivatives acting at the vertices, but these --together with loop graphs-- are higher order in the chiral expansion, and therefore constitute a small effect. This observation serves to illustrate that with heavy mesons it is not clear that the large-Nc limit is necessary in order to justify the chiral tree graph approximation.

The effective lagrangian technology which allows one to study the chiral invariant pion transitions of heavy mesons is called heavy hadron O/P T [24]. Heavy hadron O/P T provides an expansion in powers of momenta divided by \Lambda O/ , mae, and in powers of \Lambda QCD divided by the heavy hadron mass. Hence, one would expect good results for charm and bottom mesons. Mesons containing a heavy quark can be classified by the spin (s`) and the parity (ss`) of the light quark [14]. Consequently, heavy mesons fall into degenerate doublets

5 This is true only for the * = 0 sector. Recently, it has been shown that one can study pion transitions within the vector nonet in systematic fashion, since mass splittings are of order the pion mass or less [23]. Here unbroken chiral symmetry gives an interesting prediction: if the * = 1 states of the ae and the ! fill out a (2; 2) representation of SU (2) \Theta SU (2), then jg2j = 1 (see also Ref. 4).

