g = \Gamma cos(2fi+) = \Gamma g0 h = sin(2fi+); (5:7)

which again yield the entire content of Eq. (5.1), as they must. Therefore, fi+ = (` + fl)=2, and we see that the helicity zero states fix the representation content of non-zero helicity states, a consequence of the pure S-wave nature of the single-pion transitions to leading order in heavy hadron O/P T . Notice also that the non-zero helicity states are then automatically consistent with the general theorem given in Ref. 8, which we specialized to zero helicity. Similarly, there are two states with * = \Gamma 1, which can be placed in the (independent) doublet:

