Our quartet is subject to the sum rules

gh(M 2P \Lambda \Gamma M 2P 01) + hg0(M 2P \Lambda 0 \Gamma M 2P 01) = 0 gh(M 2P \Gamma M 2P \Lambda 0 ) + hg0(M 2P 01 \Gamma M 2P \Lambda 0 ) = 0; (5:10) which together with Eq. (5.1) imply

gh(M 2P \Gamma M 2P 01) = gh(M 2P \Lambda \Gamma M 2P \Lambda 0 ) = 0: (5:11) In accord with the general theorem, there are three ways to satisfy these sum rules. If the same-normality states are degenerate, then the sum rules leave the coupling constants undetermined. This option is simply not realized in nature and so in what follows we will ignore it. We then have our familiar alternatives: (i) g = 0, which implies jhj = 1, or (ii) h = 0, which implies g = \Gamma g0 = 1 or \Gamma 1. We can also see how these alternatives arise in the representation theory.

