g2flKss = 8ssf 2ss (2Jfl + 1) \Gamma totfl B (fl ! Kss)=3j~p flss j3; (7:3) where we have used Eq. (2.12). In Table 7.1 we exhibit all observed intermediate states in ssK scattering. The experimental widths are central values quoted by the particle data group [42]. There is substantial experimental uncertainty associated with some of these decays.

Keeping all intermediate states with an appreciable contribution (? 0:02), we findj gK\Lambda Kssj ' 0:66, which does not agree very well with the experimental value, jgexpK\Lambda Kssj = 0:44. According to our general conclusions, we would expect that jgK\Lambda Kssj = 1 or 0. The experimental value favors neither of these alternatives. However, the couplings of K to the set of intermediate states are generically small (see Table 7.1), and so the A-W sum rule suggests a representation content where jgK\Lambda Kssj = 1. Presumably the discrepancy arises from chiral symmetry breaking effects, which one would expect to be large, and/or the limitations of the large-Nc approximation. One might then wonder why this chiral representation content differs from that of the ground state heavy meson doublet. It is clear that the Goldstone nature of the Kaon requires that K and K\Lambda be paired. Algebraic realizations of SU (2) \Theta SU (2) accurately predict the coupling of ae to two pions (KSRF relation) [3,7]. If we consider algebraic realizations of SU (3)\Theta SU (3), the solution involving the pseudoscalar and vector octets necessarily incorporates the SU (2) \Theta SU (2) realization as a special case, and so a priori K and K\Lambda --which belong to the ss and ae SU (3) multiplets, respectively-- must communicate by single-pion emission and absorption. More specifically, SU (3) symmetry implies jhssjjXjjaeij = jhKjjXjjK\Lambda ij. Algebraic realizations of SU (2) \Theta SU (2) givejh

ssjjXjjaeij = 1, which immediately yields jgK\Lambda Kssj = 1, an interesting consistency check. With K and K\Lambda paired, the S-wave transition amplitude of any 0+ state to the ssK channel necessarily takes the smallest value that unbroken chiral symmetry allows, namely zero. In fact, K\Lambda 0 (1430) contributes very little to the A-W sum rule 10, and is a scalar with well established properties. On the other hand, we have seen that in the heavy meson system the decay amplitude of the lowest lying scalar (P \Lambda 0 ) takes the largest value allowed by unbroken chiral symmetry, and, in fact, is not observed. This is completely analogous

